# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spectral-methods
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The **Chebyshev polynomials** are two sequences of orthogonal polynomials related to the cosine and sine functions, notated as $T_{n}(x)$ and $U_{n}(x)$ .
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] That these expressions define polynomials in $\cos \theta$ is not obvious at first sight but can be shown using de Moivre's formula (see below).
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The Chebyshev polynomials *Tn* are polynomials with the largest possible leading coefficient whose absolute value on the interval [−1, 1] is bounded by 1.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] They are also the "extremal" polynomials for many other properties.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] In 1952, Cornelius Lanczos showed that the Chebyshev polynomials are important in approximation theory for the solution of linear systems; the roots of *Tn*(*x*), which are also called *Chebyshev nodes*, are used as matching points for optimizing polynomial interpolation.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The resulting interpolation polynomial minimizes the problem of Runge's phenomenon and provides an approximation that is close to the best polynomial approximation to a continuous function under the maximum norm, also called the "minimax" criterion.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] This approximation leads directly to the method of Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] These polynomials were named after Pafnuty Chebyshev.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The letter T is used because of the alternative transliterations of the name *Chebyshev* as *Tchebycheff*, *Tchebyshev* (French) or *Tschebyschow* (German).
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The Chebyshev polynomials of the first and second kind can be defined as the unique polynomials satisfying $T_{n}(\cos \theta )=\cos(n\theta )\quad$ and $U_{n}(\cos \theta )={\frac {{\sin }{\big (}(n+1)\theta {\big )}}{\sin \theta }},$ for *n* = 0, 1, 2, 3, ….
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Chebyshev polynomials can also be defined in this form when studying trigonometric polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The real part of the other side is a polynomial in $\cos x$ and $\sin x$ , in which all powers of $\sin x$ are even and thus replaceable through the identity $\cos ^{2}x+\sin ^{2}x=1$ .
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] By the same reasoning, $\sin nx$ is the imaginary part of the polynomial, in which all powers of $\sin x$ are odd and thus, if one factor of $\sin x$ is factored out, the remaining factors can be replaced to create a polynomial of degree $n-1$ in $\cos x$ .
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] This relationship is used in the Chebyshev spectral method of solving differential equations.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] where integrals are considered as principal value.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] An explicit form of the Chebyshev polynomial in terms of monomials $\textstyle x^{k}$ can be obtained as follows.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Chebyshev polynomials of odd order have odd symmetry and therefore contain only odd powers of x .
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] A Chebyshev polynomial of either kind with degree n has n different simple roots, called **Chebyshev roots**, in the interval [−1, 1].
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The roots of the Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind are sometimes called Chebyshev nodes because they are used as *nodes* in polynomial interpolation.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Thus these polynomials have only two finite critical values, the defining property of Shabat polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The derivatives of the polynomials can be less than straightforward.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Since $T_{m}(x)$ is divisible by x if m is odd, it follows that $T_{mn}(x)$ is divisible by $T_{n}(x)$ if m is odd.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Both $T_{n}$ and $U_{n}$ form a sequence of orthogonal polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] These orthogonality properties follow from the fact that the Chebyshev polynomials solve the Chebyshev differential equations ${\begin{aligned}(1-x^{2})T_{n}''-xT_{n}'+n^{2}T_{n}&=0,\\[1ex](1-x^{2})U_{n}''-3xU_{n}'+n(n+2)U_{n}&=0,\end{aligned}}$ which are Sturm–Liouville differential equations.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] It is a general feature of such differential equations that there is a distinguished orthonormal set of solutions.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] For any given $n\geq 1$ , among the polynomials of degree n with leading coefficient 1 (monic polynomials): $f(x)={\frac {1}{2^{n-1}}}T_{n}(x)$ is the one of which the maximal absolute value on the interval [−1, 1] is minimal.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Let's assume that $w_{n}(x)$ is a polynomial of degree n with leading coefficient 1 with maximal absolute value on the interval [−1, 1] less than 1 / 2*n* − 1.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] From the intermediate value theorem, *fn*(*x*) has at least n roots.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] However, this is impossible, as *fn*(*x*) is a polynomial of degree *n* − 1, so the fundamental theorem of algebra implies it has at most *n* − 1 roots.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] By the equioscillation theorem, among all the polynomials of degree ≤ *n*, the polynomial f minimizes ‖ *f* ‖∞ on [−1, 1] if and only if there are *n* + 2 points −1 ≤ *x*0 < *x*1 < ⋯ < *x**n* + 1 ≤ 1 such that | *f*(*xi*)| = ‖ *f* ‖∞.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Of course, the null polynomial on the interval [−1, 1] can be approximated by itself and minimizes the ∞-norm.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Above, however, | *f* | reaches its maximum only *n* + 1 times because we are searching for the best polynomial of degree *n* ≥ 1 (therefore the theorem evoked previously cannot be used).
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The curves given by *y* = *T**n*(*x*), or equivalently, by the parametric equations *y* = *T**n*(cos *θ*) = cos *nθ*, *x* = cos *θ*, are a special case of Lissajous curves with frequency ratio equal to n.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] This sum is called a **Chebyshev series** or a **Chebyshev expansion**.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Since a Chebyshev series is related to a Fourier cosine series through a change of variables, all of the theorems, identities, etc. that apply to Fourier series have a Chebyshev counterpart.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The Chebfun software package supports function manipulation based on their expansion in the Chebyshev basis.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Consider the Chebyshev expansion of log(1 + *x*).
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] One can find the coefficients *an* either through the application of an inner product or by the discrete orthogonality condition.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] For any N, these approximate coefficients provide an exact approximation to the function at xk with a controlled error between those points.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The exact coefficients are obtained with *N* = ∞, thus representing the function exactly at all points in [−1,1].
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The rate of convergence depends on the function and its smoothness.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The partial sums of: $f(x)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }a_{n}T_{n}(x)$ are very useful in the approximation of various functions and in the solution of differential equations (see spectral method).
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Two common methods for determining the coefficients an are through the use of the inner product as in Galerkin's method and through the use of collocation which is related to interpolation.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] As an interpolant, the N coefficients of the (*N* − 1)st partial sum are usually obtained on the Chebyshev–Gauss–Lobatto points (or Lobatto grid), which results in minimum error and avoids Runge's phenomenon associated with a uniform grid.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] An arbitrary polynomial of degree N can be written in terms of the Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Polynomials in Chebyshev form can be evaluated using the Clenshaw algorithm.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Polynomials denoted $C_{n}(x)$ and $S_{n}(x)$ closely related to Chebyshev polynomials are sometimes used.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Horadam called the polynomials $C_{n}(x)$ **Vieta–Lucas polynomials** and denoted them $v_{n}(x)$ .
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] He called the polynomials $S_{n}(x)$ **Vieta–Fibonacci polynomials** and denoted them $V_{n}(x)$ .
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] All of these polynomials have 1 as their leading coefficient.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Lists of both sets of polynomials are given in Viète's *Opera Mathematica*, Chapter IX, Theorems VI and VII.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The Vieta–Lucas and Vieta–Fibonacci polynomials of real argument are, up to a power of i and a shift of index in the case of the latter, equal to Lucas and Fibonacci polynomials *L**n* and *F**n* of imaginary argument.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] When the argument of the Chebyshev polynomial satisfies 2*x* − 1 ∈ [−1, 1] the argument of the shifted Chebyshev polynomial satisfies *x* ∈ [0, 1].
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Similarly, one can define shifted polynomials for generic intervals [*a*, *b*].
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Around 1990 the terms "third-kind" and "fourth-kind" came into use in connection with Chebyshev polynomials, although the polynomials denoted by these terms had an earlier development under the name **airfoil polynomials**.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] They coincide with the Dirichlet kernel.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] It is easier to discuss this detail by first examining the factorization of the Vieta-Lucas and Vieta-Fibonacci polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] The polynomials $\Psi _{n}(x)$ may be referred to as cyclotomic pre-polynomials, since the cyclotomic polynomials can be obtained from them via a well-defined mapping.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] An obvious property of the mapping $P_{n}(x)\rightarrow x^{n}P_{n}{\left(x+{\frac {1}{x}}\right)}$ applicable to any polynomial $P_{n}(x)$ of degree n is that it maps the product of two or more polynomials to the product of the images of the individual polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] From the irreducibility of the polynomials $\Phi _{n}(x)$ it follows that the polynomials $\Psi _{n}(x)$ are also irreducible.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Some applications rely on Chebyshev polynomials but may be unable to accommodate the lack of a root at zero, which rules out the use of standard Chebyshev polynomials for these kinds of applications.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Even order Chebyshev filter designs using equally terminated passive networks are an example of this.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] However, even order Chebyshev polynomials may be modified to move the lowest roots down to zero while still maintaining the desirable Chebyshev equi-ripple effect.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Such modified polynomials contain two roots at zero, and may be referred to as even order modified Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Even order modified Chebyshev polynomials may be created from the Chebyshev nodes in the same manner as standard Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] In the case of even order modified Chebyshev polynomials, the even order modified Chebyshev nodes are used to construct the even order modified Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] For example, the 4th order Chebyshev polynomial from the example above is $X^{4}-X^{2}+.125$ , which by inspection contains no roots of zero.
[src:spectral-methods/chebyshev-polynomials] Creating the polynomial from the even order modified Chebyshev nodes creates a 4th order even order modified Chebyshev polynomial of $X^{4}-.828427X^{2}$ , which by inspection contains two roots at zero, and may be used in applications requiring roots at zero.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] In mathematics, a **collocation method** is a method for the numerical solution of ordinary differential equations, partial differential equations and integral equations.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] The idea is to choose a finite-dimensional space of candidate solutions (usually polynomials up to a certain degree) and a number of points in the domain (called *collocation points*), and to select that solution which satisfies the given equation at the collocation points.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] This gives *n* + 1 conditions, which matches the *n* + 1 parameters needed to specify a polynomial of degree *n*.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] All these collocation methods are in fact implicit Runge–Kutta methods.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] The coefficients *c**k* in the Butcher tableau of a Runge–Kutta method are the collocation points.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] However, not all implicit Runge–Kutta methods are collocation methods.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] Pick, as an example, the two collocation points *c*1 = 0 and *c*2 = 1 (so *n* = 2).
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] There are three conditions, so *p* should be a polynomial of degree 2.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] This method is known as the "trapezoidal rule" for differential equations.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] and approximating the integral on the right-hand side by the trapezoidal rule for integrals.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] The Gauss–Legendre methods use the points of Gauss–Legendre quadrature as collocation points.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] The Gauss–Legendre method based on *s* points has order 2*s*.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] All Gauss–Legendre methods are A-stable.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] In fact, one can show that the order of a collocation method corresponds to the order of the quadrature rule that one would get using the collocation points as weights.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] In direct collocation method, we are essentially performing variational calculus with the finite-dimensional subspace of piecewise linear functions (as in trapezoidal rule), or cubic functions, or other piecewise polynomial functions.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] In orthogonal collocation method, we instead use the finite-dimensional subspace spanned by the first N vectors in some orthogonal polynomial basis, such as the Legendre polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] Top F1 teams began switching from Quasi-Static simulation to collocation methods in 2010s to simulate the time it takes for a car to go around a circuit.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] It is thought that Sauber were one of the first teams to make this transition.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] Traditional Quasi-Static simulation involves the construction of a gLat-gLong-vCar performance envelope for the car, then starting at each apex (minimum car speed) and accelerating forwards, and backwards through the braking zone using this envelope to stitch a lap together.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] It is a gross simplification of the problem because the envelope is steady state so ignores any of the dynamics that occur, for example, the car can switch instantaneously between understeer and oversteer.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] The switch to collocation methods in simulation involved casting the entire lap as an optimisation problem, broken down by distance steps around the lap which describe the car physics at each point.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] The objective is to minimise laptime and error in the physics at each point.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] Once the optimisation is complete, the collocation method finds the minimum laptime for a particular car setup around a circuit by varying brake/throttle and steering wheel angle while obeying the physics at every point.
[src:spectral-methods/collocation-method] This allows for extremely complex problems to be solved optimally.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] They are named after the Soviet mathematician Boris Galerkin.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Here, $a(\cdot ,\cdot )$ is a bilinear form (the exact requirements on $a(\cdot ,\cdot )$ will be specified later) and f is a bounded linear functional on V .
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Notice that the equation has remained unchanged and only the spaces have changed.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Reducing the problem to a finite-dimensional vector subspace allows us to numerically compute $u_{n}$ as a finite linear combination of the basis vectors in $V_{n}$ .
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] The key property of the Galerkin approach is that the error is orthogonal to the chosen subspaces.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Since $V_{n}\subset V$ , we can use $v_{n}$ as a test vector in the original equation.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Since the aim of Galerkin's method is the production of a linear system of equations, we build its matrix form, which can be used to compute the solution algorithmically.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Due to the definition of the matrix entries, the matrix of the Galerkin equation is symmetric if and only if the bilinear form $a(\cdot ,\cdot )$ is symmetric.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] While this is not really a restriction of Galerkin methods, the application of the standard theory becomes much simpler.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Furthermore, a Petrov–Galerkin method may be required in the nonsymmetric case.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] The analysis of these methods proceeds in two steps.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] First, we will show that the Galerkin equation is a well-posed problem in the sense of Hadamard and therefore admits a unique solution.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] In the second step, we study the quality of approximation of the Galerkin solution $u_{n}$ .
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] By the Lax-Milgram theorem (see weak formulation), these two conditions imply well-posedness of the original problem in weak formulation.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] All norms in the following sections will be norms for which the above inequalities hold (these norms are often called an energy norm).
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Since $V_{n}\subset V$ , boundedness and ellipticity of the bilinear form apply to $V_{n}$ .
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Therefore, the well-posedness of the Galerkin problem is actually inherited from the well-posedness of the original problem.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] This means, that up to the constant $C/c$ , the Galerkin solution $u_{n}$ is as close to the original solution u as any other vector in $V_{n}$ .
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] In particular, it will be sufficient to study approximation by spaces $V_{n}$ , completely forgetting about the equation being solved.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Dividing by $c\|u-u_{n}\|$ and taking the infimum over all possible $v_{n}$ yields the lemma.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] For simplicity of presentation in the section above we have assumed that the bilinear form $a(u,v)$ is symmetric and positive-definite, which implies that it is a scalar product and the expression ${\textstyle \|u\|_{a}={\sqrt {a(u,u)}}}$ is actually a valid vector norm, called the *energy norm*.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Under these assumptions one can easily prove in addition Galerkin's best approximation property in the energy norm.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Reddy studied the application of the Galerkin method to stepped structures.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] They showed that the generalized function, namely unit-step function, Dirac’s delta function, and the doublet function are needed for obtaining accurate results.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] The approach is usually credited to Boris Galerkin.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] The method was explained to the Western reader by Hencky and Duncan among others.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Its convergence was studied by Mikhlin and Leipholz Its coincidence with Fourier method was illustrated by Elishakoff et al.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Its equivalence to Ritz's method for conservative problems was shown by Singer.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Gander and Wanner showed how Ritz and Galerkin methods led to the modern finite element method.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] One hundred years of method's development was discussed by Repin.
[src:spectral-methods/galerkin-method] Elishakoff, Kaplunov and Kaplunov show that the Galerkin’s method was not developed by Ritz, contrary to the Timoshenko’s statements.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] In mathematics, an **orthogonal polynomial sequence** is a family of polynomials such that any two different polynomials in the sequence are orthogonal to each other under some inner product.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] The most widely used orthogonal polynomials are the classical orthogonal polynomials, consisting of the Hermite polynomials, the Laguerre polynomials and the Jacobi polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] The Gegenbauer polynomials form the most important class of Jacobi polynomials; they include the Chebyshev polynomials and the Legendre polynomials as special cases.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] These are frequently given by the Rodrigues' formula.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] The field of orthogonal polynomials developed in the late 19th century from a study of continued fractions by P.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Some of the mathematicians who have worked on orthogonal polynomials include Gábor Szegő, Sergei Bernstein, Naum Akhiezer, Arthur Erdélyi, Yakov Geronimus, Wolfgang Hahn, Theodore Seio Chihara, Mourad Ismail, Waleed Al-Salam, Richard Askey, and Rehuel Lobatto.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Given any non-decreasing function *α* on the real numbers, we can define the Lebesgue–Stieltjes integral $\int f(x)\,d\alpha (x)$ of a function *f*.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] This operation is a positive semidefinite inner product on the vector space of all polynomials, and is positive definite if the function α has an infinite number of points of growth.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] It induces a notion of orthogonality in the usual way, namely that two polynomials are orthogonal if their inner product is zero.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] In other words, the sequence is obtained from the sequence of monomials 1, *x*, *x*2, … by the Gram–Schmidt process with respect to this inner product.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Usually the sequence is required to be orthonormal, namely, $\langle P_{n},P_{n}\rangle =1,$ however, other normalisations are sometimes used.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Sometimes we have $d\alpha (x)=W(x)\,dx$ where $W:[x_{1},x_{2}]\to \mathbb {R}$ is a non-negative function with support on some interval [*x*1, *x*2] in the real line (where *x*1 = −∞ and *x*2 = ∞ are allowed).
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Such a *W* is called a **weight function**.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] The most commonly used orthogonal polynomials are orthogonal for a measure with support in a real interval.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Discrete orthogonal polynomials are orthogonal with respect to some discrete measure.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Sometimes the measure has finite support, in which case the family of orthogonal polynomials is finite, rather than an infinite sequence.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] The Racah polynomials are examples of discrete orthogonal polynomials, and include as special cases the Hahn polynomials and dual Hahn polynomials, which in turn include as special cases the Meixner polynomials, Krawtchouk polynomials, and Charlier polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Meixner classified all the orthogonal Sheffer sequences: there are only Hermite, Laguerre, Charlier, Meixner, and Meixner–Pollaczek.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] In some sense Krawtchouk should be on this list too, but they are a finite sequence.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] These six families correspond to the NEF-QVFs and are martingale polynomials for certain Lévy processes.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Sieved orthogonal polynomials, such as the sieved ultraspherical polynomials, sieved Jacobi polynomials, and sieved Pollaczek polynomials, have modified recurrence relations.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] One can also consider orthogonal polynomials for some curve in the complex plane.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] The most important case (other than real intervals) is when the curve is the unit circle, giving orthogonal polynomials on the unit circle, such as the Rogers–Szegő polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] There are some families of orthogonal polynomials that are orthogonal on plane regions such as triangles or disks.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] They can sometimes be written in terms of Jacobi polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] For example, Zernike polynomials are orthogonal on the unit disk.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] The advantage of orthogonality between different orders of Hermite polynomials is applied to Generalized frequency division multiplexing (GFDM) structure.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] More than one symbol can be carried in each grid of time-frequency lattice.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Orthogonal polynomials of one variable defined by a non-negative measure on the real line have the following properties.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] where the constants *c**n* are arbitrary (depend on the normalization of *P**n*).
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] This comes directly from applying the Gram–Schmidt process to the monomials, imposing each polynomial to be orthogonal with respect to the previous ones.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] For example, orthogonality with $P_{0}$ prescribes that $P_{1}$ must have the form $P_{1}(x)=c_{1}\left(x-{\frac {\langle P_{0},x\rangle P_{0}}{\langle P_{0},P_{0}\rangle }}\right)=c_{1}(x-m_{1}),$ which can be seen to be consistent with the previously given expression with the determinant.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] The converse is also true; see Favard's theorem.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] These recurrence relations are key for deriving properties of orthogonal polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] If the measure d*α* is supported on an interval [*a*, *b*], all the zeros of *P**n* lie in [*a*, *b*].
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Moreover, the zeros have the following interlacing property: if *m* < *n*, there is a zero of *P**n* between any two zeros of *P**m*.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Foata, and others, combinatorial interpretations were found for all the classical orthogonal polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] The Macdonald polynomials are orthogonal polynomials in several variables, depending on the choice of an affine root system.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] They include many other families of multivariable orthogonal polynomials as special cases, including the Jack polynomials, the Hall–Littlewood polynomials, the Heckman–Opdam polynomials, and the Koornwinder polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] The Askey–Wilson polynomials are the special case of Macdonald polynomials for a certain non-reduced root system of rank 1.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Multiple orthogonal polynomials are polynomials in one variable that are orthogonal with respect to a finite family of measures.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] These are orthogonal polynomials with respect to a Sobolev inner product, i.e. an inner product with derivatives.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Including derivatives has big consequences for the polynomials, in general they no longer share some of the nice features of the classical orthogonal polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Orthogonal polynomials with matrices have either coefficients that are matrices or the indeterminate is a matrix.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Quantum polynomials or q-polynomials are the q-analogs of orthogonal polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Orthogonal polynomials can be defined as a vector basis set $P_{0},P_{1},P_{2},\dots$ of a symmetric bilinear form B on polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] In the basis of the orthogonal polynomials, the bilinear form diagonalizes as $B(P_{i},P_{j})=B(P_{i},P_{i})\delta _{ij}$ .
[src:spectral-methods/orthogonal-polynomials] Similarly, given a nondegenerate skew-symmetric bilinear form on polynomials, we can find a pair of vector basis sets $P_{0},P_{1},P_{2},\dots$ and $Q_{0},Q_{1},Q_{2},\dots$ , such that the bilinear form skew-diagonalizes as $B(P_{i},Q_{j})=B(P_{i},Q_{i})\delta _{ij}$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] with periodic conditions $\psi (x+1,t)=\psi (x,t)$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] This specific example is the Schrödinger equation for a particle in a potential $V(x)$ , but the structure is more general.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] In many practical partial differential equations, one has a term that involves derivatives (such as a kinetic energy contribution), and a multiplication with a function (for example, a potential).
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] The solution would then be obtained by truncating the expansion to N basis functions, and finding a solution for the $c_{n}(t)$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] In general, this is done by numerical methods, such as Runge–Kutta methods.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] For the numerical solutions, the right-hand side of the ordinary differential equation has to be evaluated repeatedly at different time steps.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] At this point, the spectral method has a major problem with the potential term $V(x)$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] In the spectral representation, the multiplication with the function $V(x)$ transforms into a vector-matrix multiplication, which scales as $N^{2}$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] Also, the matrix elements $V_{n-k}$ need to be evaluated explicitly before the differential equation for the coefficients can be solved, which requires an additional step.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] In the pseudo-spectral method, this term is evaluated differently.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] Given the coefficients $c_{n}(t)$ , an inverse discrete Fourier transform yields the value of the function $\psi$ at discrete grid points $x_{j}=2\pi j/N$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] At these grid points, the function is then multiplied, $\psi '(x_{i},t)=V(x_{i})\psi (x_{i},t)$ , and the result Fourier-transformed back.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] This yields a new set of coefficients $c'_{n}(t)$ that are used instead of the matrix product $\sum _{k}V_{n-k}c_{k}(t)$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] It can be shown that both methods have similar accuracy.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] However, the pseudo-spectral method allows the use of a fast Fourier transform, which scales as $O(N\ln N)$ , and is therefore significantly more efficient than the matrix multiplication.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] Also, the function $V(x)$ can be used directly without evaluating any additional integrals.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] In a more abstract way, the pseudo-spectral method deals with the multiplication of two functions $V(x)$ and $f(x)$ as part of a partial differential equation.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] To simplify the notation, the time-dependence is dropped.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] For a given set of basis functions, a quadrature is sought that converts scalar products of these basis functions into a weighted sum over grid points.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] The product is calculated by multiplying $V,f$ at each grid point.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] For simplicity, let the basis be orthogonal and normalized, $\langle \phi _{n},\phi _{m}\rangle =\delta _{nm}$ using the inner product $\langle f,g\rangle =\int _{a}^{b}f(x){\overline {g(x)}}dx$ with appropriate boundaries $a,b$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] This forms the basis of the spectral method.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] To distinguish the basis of the $\phi _{n}$ from the quadrature basis, the expansion is sometimes called Finite Basis Representation (FBR).
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] Special examples are the Gaussian quadrature for polynomials and the Discrete Fourier Transform for plane waves.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] It should be stressed that the grid points and weights, $x_{i},w_{i}$ are a function of the basis *and* the number N .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] The quadrature allows an alternative numerical representation of the function $f(x),{\tilde {f}}(x)$ through their value at the grid points.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] This representation is sometimes denoted Discrete Variable Representation (DVR), and is completely equivalent to the expansion in the basis.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] This generally introduces an additional approximation.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] However, using the spectral method, the same coefficient would be ${\tilde {c}}_{n}=\langle Vf,\phi _{n}\rangle$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] If the product $Vf$ can be represented with the given finite set of basis functions, the above equation is exact due to the chosen quadrature.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] with $k_{n}=(-1)^{n}\lceil n/2\rceil 2\pi /L$ , where $\lceil \cdot \rceil$ is the ceiling function.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] The quadrature for a cut-off at $n_{\text{max}}=N$ is given by the discrete Fourier transformation.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] The grid points are equally spaced, $x_{i}=i\Delta x$ with spacing $\Delta x=L/(N+1)$ , and the constant weights are $w_{i}=\Delta x$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] For the discussion of the error, note that the product of two plane waves is again a plane wave, $\phi _{a}+\phi _{b}=\phi _{c}$ with $c\leq a+b$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] Thus, qualitatively, if the functions $f(x),V(x)$ can be represented sufficiently accurately with $N_{f},N_{V}$ basis functions, the pseudo-spectral method gives accurate results if $N_{f}+N_{V}$ basis functions are used.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] An expansion in plane waves often has a poor quality and needs many basis functions to converge.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] However, the transformation between the basis expansion and the grid representation can be done using a Fast Fourier transform, which scales favorably as $N\ln N$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] As a consequence, plane waves are one of the most common expansion that is encountered with pseudo-spectral methods.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] Another common expansion is into classical polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] holds for any polynomial $p(x)$ of degree $2N+1$ or less.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] Typically, the weight function $w(x)$ and ranges $a,b$ are chosen for a specific problem, and leads to one of the different forms of the quadrature.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] Under these conditions, the $\phi _{n}$ form an orthonormal basis with respect to the scalar product $\langle f,g\rangle =\int _{a}^{b}f(x){\overline {g(x)}}dx$ .
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] This basis, together with the quadrature points can then be used for the pseudo-spectral method.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] Such polynomials occur naturally in several standard problems.
[src:spectral-methods/pseudo-spectral-method] For example, the quantum harmonic oscillator is ideally expanded in Hermite polynomials, and Jacobi-polynomials can be used to define the associated Legendre functions typically appearing in rotational problems.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] In the numerical solution of partial differential equations, a topic in mathematics, the **spectral element method** (SEM) is a formulation of the finite element method (FEM) that uses high-degree piecewise polynomials as basis functions.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] The spectral element method was introduced in a 1984 paper by A.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] The spectral method expands the solution in trigonometric series, a chief advantage being that the resulting method is of a very high order.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] This approach relies on the fact that trigonometric polynomials are an orthonormal basis for $L^{2}(\Omega )$ .
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] The spectral element method chooses instead a high degree piecewise polynomial basis functions, also achieving a very high order of accuracy.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] Such polynomials are usually orthogonal Chebyshev polynomials or very high order Lagrange polynomials over non-uniformly spaced nodes.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] In SEM computational error decreases exponentially as the order of approximating polynomial increases, therefore a fast convergence of solution to the exact solution is realized with fewer degrees of freedom of the structure in comparison with FEM.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] In structural health monitoring, FEM can be used for detecting large flaws in a structure, but as the size of the flaw is reduced there is a need to use a high-frequency wave.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] In order to simulate the propagation of a high-frequency wave, the FEM mesh required is very fine resulting in increased computational time.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] On the other hand, SEM provides good accuracy with fewer degrees of freedom.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] Non-uniformity of nodes helps to make the mass matrix diagonal, which saves time and memory and is also useful for adopting a central difference method (CDM).
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] The disadvantages of SEM include difficulty in modeling complex geometry, compared to the flexibility of FEM.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] Although the method can be applied with a modal piecewise orthogonal polynomial basis, it is most often implemented with a nodal tensor product Lagrange basis.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] The method gains its efficiency by placing the nodal points at the Legendre-Gauss-Lobatto (LGL) points and performing the Galerkin method integrations with a reduced Gauss-Lobatto quadrature using the same nodes.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] With this combination, simplifications result such that mass lumping occurs at all nodes and a collocation procedure results at interior points.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] The most popular applications of the method are in computational fluid dynamics and modeling seismic wave propagation.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] where N is related to the discretization of the domain (ie. element length), $C_{s}$ is independent from N , and s is no larger than the degree of the piecewise polynomial basis.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] Similar results can be obtained to bound the error in stronger topologies.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] As we increase N , we can also increase the degree of the basis functions.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] The Hybrid-Collocation-Galerkin possesses some superconvergence properties.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] The LGL form of SEM is equivalent, so it achieves the same superconvergence properties.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] Development of the most popular LGL form of the method is normally attributed to Maday and Patera.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] However, it was developed more than a decade earlier.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] First, there is the Hybrid-Collocation-Galerkin method (HCGM), which applies collocation at the interior Lobatto points and uses a Galerkin-like integral procedure at element interfaces.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] The Lobatto-Galerkin method described by Young is identical to SEM, while the HCGM is equivalent to these methods.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-element-method] This earlier work is ignored in the spectral literature.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-method] Consequently, spectral methods connect variables *globally* while finite elements do so *locally*.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-method] Partially for this reason, spectral methods have excellent error properties, with the so-called "exponential convergence" being the fastest possible, when the solution is smooth.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-method] However, there are no known three-dimensional single-domain spectral shock capturing results (shock waves are not smooth).
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-method] In the finite-element community, a method where the degree of the elements is very high or increases as the grid parameter *h* increases is sometimes called a spectral-element method.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-method] Spectral methods can be used to solve differential equations (PDEs, ODEs, eigenvalue, etc) and optimization problems.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-method] When applying spectral methods to time-dependent PDEs, the solution is typically written as a sum of basis functions with time-dependent coefficients; substituting this in the PDE yields a system of ODEs in the coefficients which can be solved using any numerical method for ODEs.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-method] Eigenvalue problems for ODEs are similarly converted to matrix eigenvalue problems .
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-method] The implementation of the spectral method is normally accomplished either with collocation or a Galerkin or a Tau approach .
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-method] For very small problems, the spectral method is unique in that solutions may be written out symbolically, yielding a practical alternative to series solutions for differential equations.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-method] Spectral methods can be computationally less expensive and easier to implement than finite element methods; they shine best when high accuracy is sought in simple domains with smooth solutions.
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-method] However, because of their global nature, the matrices associated with step computation are dense and computational efficiency will quickly suffer when there are many degrees of freedom (with some exceptions, for example if matrix applications can be written as Fourier transforms).
[src:spectral-methods/spectral-method] For larger problems and nonsmooth solutions, finite elements will generally work better due to sparse matrices and better modelling of discontinuities and sharp bends.
